##WHO has the right to demand death in the face of an epidemic?

Micro-signal Jianjiaobuluo

Function description, pepper tribe, amplify your voice! Chinese Women Workers Exclusive Information Platform, you are welcome to pay attention!

ABSTRACT: This article is a contribution to the "2020, our life is continuing" essay contest. In the face of disaster, no one knows whether he will be the one who was drawn. And when that happens, what do you want people to do to you?

Wuhan is closed for 20 days, COVID-19 pneumonia outbreak nearly two months, at this point I want to write something. Not only because I am a Wuhan resident in Shanghai, but also because I am an ordinary Chinese citizen.

This Spring Festival, because of some personal reasons, I do not intend to go home to Wuhan, so I did not go home for a whole year. Just began to see the Yangtze River Daily News out of Wuhan unknown pneumonia, I did not mind, thought: is not a pneumonia, what to be afraid of.
Illustration by Emma Rooney
In 2003, the outbreak of SARS, I only on the second day, only know Banlanggen sold out, the classroom every day fumigated vinegar disinfection, back to the house by parents forced to drink Chinese medicine to prevent disease. No one around me was infected, and only 13 people in Hubei Province were infected at the time, so I had no idea what SARS was or how big it was.

On January 17th or 18th, people wearing face masks can be seen on the subway in Shanghai. As soon as I saw someone wearing a mask, I knew it was serious: pneumonia was highly contagious.
I didn't go to the drugstore right away to buy a mask, thinking I could do it whenever I wanted, and I rarely went out after I left the house naked. By the time I got to the 20th, I couldn't buy a mask. The three pharmacies near my home were out of stock. It seemed that all the pharmacies in Shanghai were out of stock. A friend bought an industrial mask at the Labor insurance supply store.
To tell the truth, I am quite bold, 21,22, I went out to see a movie on purpose. I'm a movie buff. I have a favorite movie I have to see. Besides, the tickets were booked. It's a waste not to go.

Beginning on the 21st and 22nd, almost everyone on the street began to wear masks. Following what academician Zhong Nanshan said, everyone knew that pneumonia was contagious. Only a few people, like me, walk the streets with empty faces. These people don't lack control, they just don't get it.
Later, there were many jokes on the Internet, ridiculing the elderly do not wear masks, do not obey the management, I think some of them may really do not care, but most people should be no mask to wear.
Older people are less resistant, may have underlying diseases, and have higher rates of pneumonia and death from the disease than younger people. They are ill-informed, single-source of purchase, in the event of an epidemic is bad enough, but also bear the blame. I'm really sorry about some of the jokes.
After the movie, I decided never to go out again. In order to celebrate the New Year, I had stockpiled some vegetables, fruits, oil, salt seasoning, rice grains are sufficient. By the evening of the 22nd, my state of mind is steady, although a little scared, but only a little, not be "black death" (scared to death) .

Photograph: PNGTREE
When I got up on the morning of the 23rd and saw the news about the closure of the city of Wuhan, I was devastated.
I am very, very panic, immediately contact family and friends to inquire about the situation, and online information, to find out the meaning of the city, the follow-up development of the disease, the security of citizens, and so on. My family's fine, but I'm still scared to death. I didn't think it was gonna get this big, and I don't know what's GonNa Happen, but what if it gets worse?
At first I could barely keep my cool as my best friend in Wuhan scolded me for the Wuhan government's inaction, and I defended them. The administrative system and the body muscles are the same, usually more exercise only at the critical moment. Wuhan, as a second-tier city, rarely undertake large-scale international events, and no strong economic strength to support, all of a sudden on such a big event, of course, panic, do not do well also excusable.
But then the news just got angrier and angrier.
First of all the major hospitals medical supplies are in urgent need, have started to ask for social assistance. Then came the fever clinic in People Mountain People Sea, where patients could not be treated effectively and health care workers were overworked. The city's public transport system was shut down, takeout was not delivered to hospitals, and medical staff had problems commuting and eating.
A lot of patients die at home before they're diagnosed, and the cause of death can only be viral pneumonia. A hospital bed is hard to find, a large number of patients dragged between the hospitals, unable to find beds and spread the disease. Various thorny problems emerge one after another, government departments will only block traffic, but no concrete measures for the people to solve problems.
The city seemed to be paralyzed, with ordinary people and front-line soldiers struggling like drowning men. The general public began to save themselves, citizens spontaneously organized a convoy of medical personnel to and from work, the hotel provided free accommodation for medical personnel, the restaurant insisted on business for the hospital.
The anger that grows out of empathy burns and destroys reason. These are human lives. Why would I do that now? In the beginning, if we had done something right away, we could have ended up like this? I was so anxious, I couldn't sleep for days on end, and I wanted to cry every day, and the next thing I knew, it was beyond my imagination.
Photograph: PNGTREE
On the 25th, my colleague in Shanghai asked me out of the blue how things were in Wuhan, if it was much worse than reported. I don't know the details, but I know there are quite a few people waiting to be diagnosed.
He told me about a woman in Wuhan who had a fever and a mother in Wuhan who drove to the Shanghai hospital with a feverish baby. More than 300,000 people fled Wuhan before the city was officially sealed off, with Shanghai the preferred destination for most.
In fact, the lady at the gate of the global port was just sick, no fever, neither Wuhan people, nor to Wuhan. As for the news that Wuhan Mother took her child to see a doctor, it was like a rumor that the child only had a normal cold and fever.
It is nonsense that more than 300,000 people fled Wuhan before the city was formally sealed off. Wuhan Sanzhen Railway Station sends around 15 million people each year during the Spring Festival, and 300,000 passengers between 2 am and 10 am on the 23rd. Isn't that normal? What's wrong with taking the train home when the passengers have already bought their train tickets? Should they all return their tickets and stay in Wuhan for the greater good?
The vast majority of those 300,000-plus people are migrant workers who have no family or permanent residence in Wuhan and may not be able to eat a hot meal after the shops close for the Spring Festival. At present, people's most honest and sincere idea is to go home, and family gathered together what is not afraid of. About 75 percent of these people went to other cities in Hubei Province, with the rest going to neighboring provinces. They're just going home.
If a few escape with the hope of escaping the plague, they are fleeing. What's wrong with a man trying to find a way to live? If it were you, wouldn't you run?
You've seen the news these days. The number of confirmed cases in Hubei remained high. As of the 11th, the total number of confirmed cases in Hubei was 31,728, accounting for 74.3 percent of the whole country. The case fatality rate in Wuhan and Hubei was 4.61% and 2.94% , respectively. The case fatality rate in Hubei was 8.4 times that in other regions, and 0.35% in other regions.
Not only is Hubei more likely to get the disease, it is also more likely to die. And that's just the statistics that came in after the diagnosis, but more people actually died from the pneumonia.
I was incensed by the arrogance of my colleagues. He was lucky enough to be sitting at home in Shanghai, not a hard hit area, with the country's best medical care. He even went so far as to accuse the people of Hubei Province of bringing the virus to Shanghai on the basis of false news.
Image Credit: Illustrator KLEMT
No Man is inferior to another. It is the duty of the people of the affected areas to be strong, but not to sacrifice their lives for the sake of the whole country. No one is more noble than who, those who live in the non-epidemic areas may think they are a bit too expensive. It's like there's a fire, and the people in the center of it are dying, and the people out there are just screaming at each other because they've been burned by the sparks.
You can't ask people to magnify their risks for your own safety. All men are created equal. There is no such thing as a high or low life. From the overall situation, sealing off the city to cut off all personnel flow is the best choice. Individually, who wants to be the one who gets sacrificed?
Wuhan is a heroic city, the people of Wuhan are heroic people, nearly 10 million Wuhan residents put their lives on the line to secure the epidemic area, some of them have paid the cost of their lives, this only in exchange for the control of the epidemic in other parts of the country. They've given enough.
You want to say it's all Wuhan People's fault, who told them to eat game? Only a few Wuhan residents eat game, the vast majority of people are innocent, are victims. Not to mention, there are so many places to eat venison, it is unfortunate that Wuhan was just drawn by the devil.
Even if the game is contained, there may be another outbreak of a major epidemic. You never know if you're GONNA be the one who gets picked. And when that happens, what do you want people to do to you? To support you, to help you, or to see you as a god of plague, to avoid or even to put to death?
I'm not saying this because I'm from Wuhan. Let's say I'm from Shanghai, i would say to the people in the Shanghai Epidemic Area: "please do a good job of protection, timely report of the disease, do not hide, Shanghai will certainly help you. ". Don't be afraid, if you have something to do, you can do it together. Shanghai's first-class medical system is your strongest support."
Because I know that hostility and vilification will not produce any value, will only make people fear, hiding the disease delay treatment, resulting in the spread of the epidemic.
Because I know they're my people, and they're fighting for their lives, and I can't let them die.
For Yourself, for others, please be kind.
Thank you to the medical staff of Hubei Province.
